The following is a paraphrase of an editorial by Kurt Kister in the
Munich SUEDDEUTSCHE ZEITUNG.

Clinton's early days in office were marked by a near disaster: an ill-
considered attempt to lift the ban on homosexuals in the U.S. Army,
rejection of candidates for important offices and failure to follow
through on campaign promises regarding Haiti and Bosnia.  He seemed to
flounder.

A year later Clinton enjoys a 60% popularity.  The economy is up,
prices stable and interest low.  The deficit is lower and Clinton's
thrift measures have helped attain this goal. The NAFTA treaty was
skillfully handled and a national health plan is in the works.

Clinton seems to have reestablished America's trust in itself.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900608-0009"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">    

Governor Bill Clinton won his sixth straight primary election by 55%,
a drop from previous years.  He has no cause for concern jokingly
citing the "tenure" issue, meaning, "ten years is long enough," used
by his opponent.

He counters, "a business wouldn't fire a 43-year old with ten years of
experience who's doing a good job."

Clinton has focused on improving Arkansas' educational system and
calls himself the candidate of change.

He was elected first in 1978 but lost in 1980.  He won again in '82,
'84, and '86, when the term was increased to four years.  He has
implied that if he is elected this year, he will not run for president
in 1992.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ920214-0040"
