SUMMARIZER="K">   
 
Last week the Wall Street Journal published an article on how Clinton
avoided the Vietnam draft.

Like many his age, he wanted a draft deferment. Graduate school
deferments had ended.  His draft board told him he could expect to be
called in the fall of 1969; giving him extra consideration because he
was a Rhodes Scholar.  Clinton went back to Oxford.

Later he found an ROTC program at the University of Arkansas,
promising to enroll. He entered Yale.

Near his induction date, he ended his deferment and was placed in the
draft lottery; a high number ensured his exclusion.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ920312-0114"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">  
   
Bill Clinton's friends came to his aid when charges of draft dodging
were raised.  A group from Oxford all testified of his anguish over
his draft status.

Later, when the draft and womanizing issues threatened, friends like
San Nunn and Zell Miller came to his rescue.

Mr. Clinton has cultivated friends all his life and always maintained
relationships through calls and notes.  Individuals from Georgetown,
Oxford, Yale and the Renaissance policy organization make up this
group.  They have helped him by raising money, managing campaigns and
defending him in crises.

Clinton knows how to make friends, and how to use them.  </SUM>

<SUM
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ920206-0058"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="K">    

In 1969 it appeared Bill Clinton would be drafted.  Studying at Oxford
wouldn't help; such deferments had ended in 1966.

The draft board in Arkansas was proud of him and had deferred him to 
go to Oxford, saying he'd be safe till fall, 1969.	
	 
As an out, he agreed in 1969 to join the ROTC at the University of
Arkansas.  He never enrolled, but it protected him during September
and October of 1969.  By October he subjected himself to the draft
lottery knowing that he was unlikely to be called.  He drew 311--and
was safe from induction.  </SUM>
